- When copying the teams, the names are the same, the looks are the same, the titles and the logo are the same.
- E.g. tp0 is Chicago Bulls, if you copy this to be also tp1, tp2, tp3, then they will all be Chicago bools
- Useful info: When changing the team files while the game is running on the main screen, they are refreshed. This means, they are loaded dynamically, not pre-loaded in the beginning of the game.

- Next question is, how similar are the teams binary files?
- To begin with, all the files are of the same size. What does that mean in practice? First of all that, the length of the surnames does not really matter. They are either appended with spaces until the maximum length, or they are stored somehow somewhere else and the team file only contains a pointer.

- Starting from byte 1000 replacing 1000 bytes from tp2 to tp1 and storting the result in tp0
That makes Chicago Bulls to be Boston Celtics with some parts of East All-Stars! Part of the logo is Bulls, another part is East All Stars. Cummings is now playing instead of Bird. The rest of the players are the same in the starting 5. From the subs, Barkley and Daugherty are there instead of Acres and Birdsong. That means that the players are not in the order they appear. But "Barkley" is white in this case! So it has the looks of Acres but it shows Barkley?!

