Memory areas:
0 - 800: The name of the team is changed. Doesn't seem to cause any visual difference in the teams, logo and players. The game plays fine.
0 - 400: The upper part of the name
400-800 Changes the name to Los Angeles Celtics. I.e. transfers only the lower part of the name
826 - 1610: is the logo (784 bytes?) Setting 111111 makes it same as the background, 00000000 sets it black

- Player names start 1608, for 132 bytes, they are in sequence, if you double the bytes, the names are affected but not the statistics! Nor the looks.
- 6 pixels height, 22 pixels wide, 132 bytes per player.
After this we end up to an offset of 3192. Interesting stuff starts happening there. It seems to be the pointers for the players, meaning, what player is chosen from some database somewhere.

- Put a "00" starting there and you will get A Jabbar instead of Worthy.
- 01 shows black info!?
- 02
- 03 is also weird?!

- So it seems that every odd number is ... odd!? The last bit leads to shit? Could it be endianness??

 - So changing the first byte from 16 to 17, Jabbar appears as worthy, shorter (?) and with slightly shifted t-shirt!?

 - So indeed even if you try to write a byte as binary, as long as it contains a 1 in the end the name will be garbage. 
And actually in the original data from Los Angeles lakers you see:
3192 3204(b'\x16\x06\x00\x08\x10\x02\x04\n\x0c\x0e\x12\x14')
No odd number.
